"lat":37.32143,"lng":-81.29151,"mile":5.7,"ele":843},{"name":"Bramwell Lake","type":"lake","lat":37.31668,"lng":-81.3033,"mile":6.3,"ele":758},{"name":"Shawnee Mountain","type":"peak","lat":37.40345,"lng":-81.43538,"mile":17.7,"ele":851},{"name":"Joes Branch Refuse Impoundment","type":"lake","lat":37.56374,"lng":-81.45402,"mile":58.9,"ele":516}],"gallery":[{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/20/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_A_Millionaire%27s_Mansion%2C_the_Goodwill_House_in_Bramwell_-_NARA_-_7717664.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_A_Millionaire%27s_Mansion%2C_the_Goodwill_House_in_Bramwell_-_NARA_-_7717664.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/20/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_A_Millionaire%27s_Mansion%2C_the_Goodwill_House_in_Bramwell_-_NARA_-_7717664.jpg","cap":"A Millionaire's Mansion, the Goodwill House in Bramwell","desc":"The Goodwill House overlooks historic Bramwell, home to many coal barons who began the coal industry in southern West Virginia. Location: West Virginia (37.325° N 81.312° W) Status: Public domain. Courtesy of West Virginia Division of Tourism","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_A_Millionaire%27s_Mansion,_the_Goodwill_House_in_Bramwell_-_NARA_-_7717664.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_A_Road_Through_Mount_Hope_Historic_District_-_NARA_-_7717651.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_A_Road_Through_Mount_Hope_Historic_District_-_NARA_-_7717651.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a2/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_A_Road_Through_Mount_Hope_Historic_District_-_NARA_-_7717651.jpg","cap":"A Road Through Mount Hope Historic District","desc":"An empty street runs between the redbrick buildings of the Mount Hope Historic District on a gray day. Location: Mount Hope, West Virginia (37.896° N 81.164° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by David Hafley","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_A_Road_Through_Mount_Hope_Historic_District_-_NARA_-_7717651.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/93/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Bank_of_Glen_Jean_-_NARA_-_7717650.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Bank_of_Glen_Jean_-_NARA_-_7717650.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/93/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Bank_of_Glen_Jean_-_NARA_-_7717650.jpg","cap":"Bank of Glen Jean","desc":"The Bank of Glen Jean, built by Thomas McKell in 1909, is constructed of random broken ashlar stone in a soft yellow color and emanates a strong and solid presence due to its excellent construction (28-inch thick walls) and history of operation by the McKell family. Location: Glen Jean, West Virginia (37.927° N 81.151° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by Molly Davis","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Bank_of_Glen_Jean_-_NARA_-_7717650.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Buildings_of_the_Fayetteville_Historic_District_-_NARA_-_7717654.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Buildings_of_the_Fayetteville_Historic_District_-_NARA_-_7717654.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/10/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Buildings_of_the_Fayetteville_Historic_District_-_NARA_-_7717654.jpg","cap":"Buildings of the Fayetteville Historic District","desc":"Along an unpopulated street in Fayetteville stands many historic structures still in use today. The Fayette County National Bank was constructed in 1906-1907 from native stone hauled from the Cotton Hill area. Location: Fayetteville, West Virginia (38.053° N 81.104° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by Molly Davis","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Buildings_of_the_Fayetteville_Historic_District_-_NARA_-_7717654.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Canyon_Rim_Visitor_Center_-_NARA_-_7717657.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Canyon_Rim_Visitor_Center_-_NARA_-_7717657.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a7/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Canyon_Rim_Visitor_Center_-_NARA_-_7717657.jpg","cap":"Canyon Rim Visitor Center","desc":"With lush green trees and a sidewalk lined with people, the Canyon Rim Visitor Center for the New River Gorge National River provides interpretive exhibits about the historic relationship between the New River and the members of the area's mining communities. Location: New River Gorge, West Virginia (38.071° N 81.076° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by Molly Davis","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Canyon_Rim_Visitor_Center_-_NARA_-_7717657.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Chimney_Corner_-_NARA_-_7717646.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Chimney_Corner_-_NARA_-_7717646.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/86/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Chimney_Corner_-_NARA_-_7717646.jpg","cap":"Chimney Corner","desc":"A small country store on the right side of the curving road is surrounded by hills and rugged landscape at Chimney Corner. Location: Chimney Corner, West Virginia (38.139° N 81.147° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by Molly Davis","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Chimney_Corner_-_NARA_-_7717646.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Fayette_Station_Road_-_NARA_-_7717645.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Fayette_Station_Road_-_NARA_-_7717645.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5a/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Fayette_Station_Road_-_NARA_-_7717645.jpg","cap":"Fayette Station Road","desc":"A pull-off on Fayette Station Road showcases the New River Gorge Bridge through the leafy foliage of summer. Location: New River Gorge, West Virginia (38.069° N 81.083° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by Molly Davis","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Fayette_Station_Road_-_NARA_-_7717645.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/14/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Historic_Main_Street_in_Bramwell_-_NARA_-_7717659.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Historic_Main_Street_in_Bramwell_-_NARA_-_7717659.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/14/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Historic_Main_Street_in_Bramwell_-_NARA_-_7717659.jpg","cap":"Historic Main Street in Bramwell","desc":"Main Street in Bramwell remains virtually unchanged from the days when coal was king, and Bramwell was home to 14 millionaires. Location: Bramwell, West Virginia (37.325° N 81.312° W) Status: Public domain. Courtesy of West Virginia Division of Tourism","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Historic_Main_Street_in_Bramwell_-_NARA_-_7717659.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/96/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Inside_the_Beckley_Exhibition_Coal_Mine_Visitor_Center_-_NARA_-_7717647.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/96/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Inside_the_Beckley_Exhibition_Coal_Mine_Visitor_Center_-_NARA_-_7717647.jpg","cap":"Inside the Beckley Exhibition Coal Mine Visitor Center","desc":"Children and adult visitors look at miner tool exhibits at the Beckley Exhibition Coal Mine Visitor Center. Location: Beckley, West Virginia (37.778° N 81.200° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by Scott Marx","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Inside_the_Beckley_Exhibition_Coal_Mine_Visitor_Center_-_NARA_-_7717647.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Itmann_Company_Store_-_NARA_-_7717668.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Itmann_Company_Store_-_NARA_-_7717668.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/da/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Itmann_Company_Store_-_NARA_-_7717668.jpg","cap":"Itmann Company Store","desc":"Light catches the stone facade of the Historic Itmann Company Store. Location: West Virginia (37.326° N 81.314° W) Status: Public domain.","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Itmann_Company_Store_-_NARA_-_7717668.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9a/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Little_Girl_with_a_Big_Fish_-_NARA_-_7717663.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9a/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Little_Girl_with_a_Big_Fish_-_NARA_-_7717663.jpg","cap":"Little Girl with a Big Fish","desc":"A little girl holds up her prized catch of the day along the New River in West Virginia. Location: West Virginia Status: Public domain. National Park Service","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Little_Girl_with_a_Big_Fish_-_NARA_-_7717663.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Looking_at_the_New_River_from_Hawk%27s_Nest_State_Park_-_NARA_-_7717655.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Looking_at_the_New_River_from_Hawk%27s_Nest_State_Park_-_NARA_-_7717655.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e0/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Looking_at_the_New_River_from_Hawk%27s_Nest_State_Park_-_NARA_-_7717655.jpg","cap":"Looking at the New River from Hawk's Nest State Park","desc":"Displaying a wealth of fall reds, yellows, and golds in the deciduous trees in the surrounding mountains, the view from an overlook at Hawk's Nest State Park provides a look far into the West Virginian distance. Location: Hawk's Nest State Park, West Virginia (38.122° N 81.123° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by WV Division of Tourism","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Looking_at_the_New_River_from_Hawk%27s_Nest_State_Park_-_NARA_-_7717655.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/70/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_New_River_Company_Cranberry_Store_-_NARA_-_7717648.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_New_River_Company_Cranberry_Store_-_NARA_-_7717648.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/70/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_New_River_Company_Cranberry_Store_-_NARA_-_7717648.jpg","cap":"New River Company Cranberry Store","desc":"Constructed of brick with a stone lintel inscribed with \"New River Company Cranberry Store,\" the building has fallen upon hard times, as witnessed by the numerous bathtubs and radiators positioned on the porch and in front of the building, as well as piles of unknown materials inside. Location: West Virginia (38.052° N 81.105° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by Molly Davis","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_New_River_Company_Cranberry_Store_-_NARA_-_7717648.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/be/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_New_River_Gorge_Bridge_From_Above_-_NARA_-_7717658.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_New_River_Gorge_Bridge_From_Above_-_NARA_-_7717658.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/be/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_New_River_Gorge_Bridge_From_Above_-_NARA_-_7717658.jpg","cap":"New River Gorge Bridge From Above","desc":"The massive steel structure supporting the bridge is visible under US 19 as it travels into the distance on a misty and foggy day. Location: New River Gorge, West Virginia (38.069° N 81.083° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by Steve Shaluta","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_New_River_Gorge_Bridge_From_Above_-_NARA_-_7717658.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Pocahontas_Cemetery_-_NARA_-_7717666.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Pocahontas_Cemetery_-_NARA_-_7717666.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5d/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Pocahontas_Cemetery_-_NARA_-_7717666.jpg","cap":"Pocahontas Cemetery","desc":"Bare trees line the way to the final resting ground of Pocahontas. Location: West Virginia (37.309° N 81.334° W) Status: Public domain.","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_Pocahontas_Cemetery_-_NARA_-_7717666.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/14/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_The_Depot_in_Bramwell%2C_West_Virginia_-_NARA_-_7717660.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/14/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_The_Depot_in_Bramwell%2C_West_Virginia_-_NARA_-_7717660.jpg","cap":"The Depot in Bramwell, West Virginia","desc":"This reconstructed train depot serves as an information center and the southern interpretive center for The Coal Heritage Trail. Location: West Virginia (37.325° N 81.312° W) Status: Public domain. Courtesy of Coal Heritage Highway Authority","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_The_Depot_in_Bramwell,_West_Virginia_-_NARA_-_7717660.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_The_Halfway_House_in_Ansted_-_NARA_-_7717656.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_The_Halfway_House_in_Ansted_-_NARA_-_7717656.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2e/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_The_Halfway_House_in_Ansted_-_NARA_-_7717656.jpg","cap":"The Halfway House in Ansted","desc":"Also called Tyree Tavern, the gray-roofed, white-walled Halfway House would have been much more active during the time travelers such as Daniel Webster, Henry Clay and John Breckenridge sought the shortest east-west route between the Blue Ridge and Allegheny mountains. Location: Ansted, West Virginia (38.136° N 81.099° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by Molly Davis","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_The_Halfway_House_in_Ansted_-_NARA_-_7717656.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_The_World%27s_Second_Longest_Single_Arch_Steel_Span%2C_the_New_River_Gorge_Bridge_-_NARA_-_7717649.jpg/1280px-Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_The_World%27s_Second_Longest_Single_Arch_Steel_Span%2C_the_New_River_Gorge_Bridge_-_NARA_-_7717649.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/38/Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_The_World%27s_Second_Longest_Single_Arch_Steel_Span%2C_the_New_River_Gorge_Bridge_-_NARA_-_7717649.jpg","cap":"The World's Second Longest Single Arch Steel Span, the New River Gorge","desc":"An engineering feat and regional icon, the New River Gorge Bridge connects the flourishing, green east and west banks of the river between two previously isolated communities. Location: New River Gorge, West Virginia (38.069° N 81.083° W) Status: Public domain. Photograph by David E. Fattaleh","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coal_Heritage_Trail_-_The_World%27s_Second_Longest_Single_Arch_Steel_Span,_the_New_River_Gorge_Bridge_-_NARA_-_7717649.jpg"}]}